  <section>
    <title>The Axiom of Completeness</title>
<p> What is the author trying to do?  No, let me ask a more general question.  What are some vocab terms that have come up, in class and the reading?</p>
<p><ul>
    <li>DeMorgan's Law</li>
    <li>supremum, infimum</li>
    <li>set bounds:  upper, lower, total</li>
    <li>triangle inequality</li>
    <li>(proof techniques)</li>
    <li><m>\mathbb{N}</m>, <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>, <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>, <m>\mathbb{Q}^c</m>, <m>\mathbb{R}</m>,</li>
</ul></p>
    <p>What are the basic operations endowed to <m>\mathbb{N}</m>, <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>, and <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>?</p>

    <p workspace="2in">Note how these n umber systems are nested and how one allows us to get to the next until we get to <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>.</p>


    <p>To get to <m>\mathbb{Z}</m> from <m>\mathbb{N}</m> we add the additive inverses to <m>\mathbb{N}</m> and zero.</p>
    <p>To get to <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> from <m>\mathbb{Z}</m> we add the multiplicative inverses to <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>.</p>
    <p>It's not clear how to get from <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}</m> ... it's like we can't do it without working from the outside of <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>.  This is where the <term>Axiom of Completeness</term> comes into play; it is how we pass from <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>

        <theorem>
            <title>Axiom of Completeness</title>
            <statement>
                <p>If <m>A</m> is a nonempty set that is bonded above, then it has a least upper bound.</p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>

        <p>The set <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> does not obey the Axiom of Completeness because <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> doesn't have sufficient numbers (<em>i.e.</em> the irrationals).  To get the reals, we take <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> and add all the numbers required for the new set to satisfy the Axiom of Completeness.</p>
        <p>This addition <term>completes</term> the rationals and gives us the real number system, <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
        <p>Our take-away from this process should be that the reals are a <term>complete</term> number system that have all the nive field properties of the rationals.</p>
</section>

<section>
    <title>Maxima and suprema</title>

    <definition>
        <statement>
            <p>A real number <m>a_0</m> is a <term>maximum</term> of <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> if
                <ol>
                    <li><m>a_0 \in A</m>, and</li>
                    <li><m>a \leq a_0</m> for all <m>a \in A</m>.</li>
                </ol></p>
            <p>A real number <m>a_0</m> is a <term>minimum</term> of <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> if
                <ol>
                    <li><m>a_0 \in A</m>, and</li>
                    <li><m>a \geq a_0</m> for all <m>a \in A</m>.</li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
        <statement>
            A finite set of real numbers always has both a minimum and a maximum.
        </statement>
        <answer>
            Why?  Real numbers can be ordered, so we can order our finite collection of numbers.  Then we can see it will have a least element and a greatest element.  The least is the minimum of the set and the greatest is the maximum of the set.
        </answer>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            The open interval <m>(0,1)=\{x \in \mathbb{R} \, : \, 0 &lt; x &lt; 1 \}</m>.  What is its maximum?  What is its minimum?
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>This set does not have a maximum.  One might want to say 1 is a maximum, but it is not an element of the set, so it cannot be a maximum.  If you take a number that is a tiny bit smaller, then you can find a number in the interval that is bigger than your new number, so your new number can't be a maximum.</p>
            <p>The same type of argument explains why the interval does not have a minimum, either.
            </p>
        </answer>
    </example>

    </section>

<section>
    <title>Maxima and suprema</title>

    <definition>
        <statement>
            Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be nonempty.  The real number <m>s</m> is a <term>least upper bound</term> (aka <term>supremum</term>) of <m>A</m> if
                <ol>
                    <li><m>s</m> is an upper bound for <m>A</m>, and</li>
                    <li>if <m>M</m> is another upper bound, then <m>s \leq M</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            The real number <m>\ell</m> is a <term>greatest lower bound</term> (aka <term>infimum</term>) of <m>A</m> if
                <ol>
                    <li><m>\ell</m> is an lower bound for <m>A</m>, and</li>
                    <li>if <m>m</m> is another lower bound, then <m>m \leq \ell</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>For each of the following sets, determine its infimum, supremum, minimum, and maximum or decide that it does not exist.
            <ol>
                <li><m>A=\{ \frac{1}{n} \, : \, n \in \mathbb{N} \}</m></li>
                <li><m>B=\{ \frac{1}{n} \, : \, n \in \mathbb{Z} \setminus \{0\} \, \}</m></li>
                <li><m>C=[0,1] \cup [2,3]</m></li>
                <li><m>D=\bigcap_{i=1}^{\infty} [-\frac{1}{n},1+\frac{1}{n}]</m></li>
                <li><m>E=\{ x \in \mathbb{R} \, : \, x &lt; 0\}</m></li>
                <li><m>F=\bigcap_{i=1}^{\infty} (1-\frac{1}{n},1+\frac{1}{n})</m></li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        
        
            <p>
                <tabular>
                    <row header="yes"><cell>Set</cell><cell>sup</cell><cell>inf</cell><cell>max</cell><cell>min</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>A</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>0</cell><cell>DNE</cell><cell>1</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>B</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>-1</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>-1</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>C</cell><cell>3</cell><cell>0</cell><cell>3</cell><cell>0</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>D</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>0</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>0</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>E</cell><cell>0</cell><cell>DNE</cell><cell>DNE</cell><cell>DNE</cell></row>
                    <row><cell>F</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>1</cell></row>
                </tabular>
            </p>
       </statement>
    </example>
    
    </section>

<section>
    <title>Maxima and suprema</title>       
    <theorem>
        <statement>
            <p>Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a nonempty set that is bonded above.  Let <m>s \in \mathbb{R}</m> be an uppoer bound for <m>A</m>. Then <m>s=\sup(A)</m> if and only if, for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> with <m>s-\epsilon a</m>.</p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>We will prove this Lemma next time.</p>
    <note><p>With this lemma we will have two ways of proving statements about suprema:  the definition (to make arguments from first principles), and this lemma (which is an equivalent characterization of suprema).</p></note>
</section>



